raphic or habitational name referring to a house named with this word.","Jewish (eastern Ashkenazic): variant of   Abt  , a habitational name from Opatów in Poland."]},{"name":"Apter","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Jewish Avrohom, Bronya, Eliezer, Naftali.","Jewish (Ashkenazic): habitational name for someone from Apt (see   Apt  ).","English: habitational name from Aptor in Marldon, Devon, composed of Old English <i>uppe</i> ‘up, above’ + <i>torr</i> ‘rocky outcrop’."]}]},{"name":"Thomas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["New Testament name, borne by one of Christ's twelve apostles, referred to as ‘Thomas, called Didymus’ (John 11:16; 20:24). <i>Didymos</i> is the Greek word for ‘twin’, and the name is the Greek form of an Aramaic byname meaning ‘twin’. The given name has always been popular throughout Christendom, in part because St Thomas's doubts have made him seem a very human character."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"Mrs. Thomas ap Ieuan was born about 1296, in Aberllynfi, Breconshire, Wales. She had at least 2 sons with Thomas Ap Ieuan."},"et":{"about 1296–":"umbes 1296–Surnud","1272–Male":"1272–Surnud","1302–Male":"1302–Surnud","1346–Male":"1346–Surnud","1296–Female":"1296–Surnud","1346":"1346","1302":"1302","about 1302":"umbes 1302","about 1346":"umbes 1346","1296":"1296","1272":"1272","about 1296":"umbes 1296","Llansannor, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llansannor, Glamorgan, Wales","Aberllynfi, Breconshire, Wales":"Aberllynfi, Breconshire, Wales"},"fi":{"about 1296–":"noin 1296–Kuollut","1272–Male":"1272–Kuollut","1302–Male":"1302–Kuollut","1346–Male":"1346–Kuollut","1296–Female":"1296–Kuollut","1346":"1346","1302":"1302","about 1302":"noin 1302","about 1346":"noin 1346","1296":"1296","1272":"1272","about 1296":"noin 1296","Llansannor, Glamorgan, Wales":"Llansannor, Glamorgan, Wales","Aberllynfi, Breconshire, Wales":"Aberllynfi, Breconshire, Wales"},"fr":{"about 129